NOTE — probe_dooriv_worstb_crossprime_index.py — SCAN-ARTIFACT WARNING + verdict

ARTIFACT CAUGHT (and FIXED) during this probe's own development:
  The first run used a STRIDED subsample `range(0, k, k//KMAX_SCAN)` for large k (n=32,64). At n=32
  the stride is 8, so only indices j ≡ 0 (mod 8) were ever scanned => the worst-index residue came
  out "all ≡ 0 (mod 4)" ([14,0,0,0]) — a PURE SCAN ARTIFACT, not arithmetic structure. This is the
  SAME trap that deprecated probe_dooriv_worstb_class_structure.py (v1). FIX: random.sample (seed 444),
  uniform over Z_k, which makes j mod d unbiased by construction.

VERDICT (after the fix — random uniform subsample, EXACT phase sums, prize regime p≈n^4≫n^3, proper μ_n):
  The worst-b coset INDEX is prime-independently DELOCALIZED.
    - normalized position j*/k: mean≈0.41–0.56, sd≈0.31–0.33 across n=16,32,64
      (uniform(0,1) reference: mean 0.5, sd 0.289) — statistically indistinguishable from uniform.
    - j* mod 2,3,4: uniform at every n (the n=32 [14,0] vanished to [7,7] once the stride bias was removed).
  => No repeatable arithmetic rule selects the adversarial frequency across primes. The worst b is not
     a prime-independent arithmetic object; a TARGETED (non-energy, non-sum-product) anti-concentration
     bound has no prime-stable structural target to grip. This closes the door-(iv) Lane-1 hope
     "the worst-b SET is prime-independently structured". Complements (does not subsume): the SINGLE-prime
     worst-b structure probes (gcd/sublattice/QR/v2 scattered) and probe_444_worstb_const_prime_stability
     (which pinned the worst-b COHERENCE CONSTANT C but said nothing about the INDEX identity across primes).
  NON-CLAIM: this is a refutation of a selection-structure hope, NOT a CORE bound. CORE stays OPEN.

Formal kernel: ArkLib/Data/CodingTheory/ProximityGap/Frontier/_DoorIVWorstIndexDelocalized.lean
  (axiom-clean): a worst-index family that is full-range and residue-unbiased admits no fixed-residue /
  fixed-position prime-independent selection rule.
